{% block bodyContent %}
  
{{ designExample({
  group: "components",
  item: "section-navigation",
  type: "default"
}) }}

<h2 id="when-to-use">When to use section navigation</h2>
<p>Use the section navigation component when users need to move between related pages in a service. For example, if your service is a case management system, you could use section navigation where there are several pages associated with a single case.</p>
<p>It is designed for staff-facing services that staff use repeatedly.</p>

<h2 id="when-not-to-use">When not to use section navigation</h2>
<p>Do not use section navigation as the primary navigation in a service. Use the <a href="/design-system/components/header">header component</a> with the navigation option.</p>
<p>Be careful about using it on content-heavy public websites. Users may scroll past section navigation on content pages. Other patterns may help users navigate content better, for example, the:</p>
<ul>
    <li><a href="/design-system/patterns/hub-page">hub page pattern</a></li>
    <li><a href="/design-system/patterns/mini-hub">mini hub pattern</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Do not use this component for links between sections of the same page. If you need to organise large amounts of content on a single page, consider:</p>
<ul>
    <li>cutting the content back</li>
    <li>using headings</li>    
    <li><a href="/design-system/components/details">details</a></li>
    <li><a href="/design-system/components/expander">expanders</a></li>
    <li><a href="/design-system/components/tabs">tabs</a></li>
</ul>

<p>Details, expanders and tabs hide sections of content on a page which a user can choose to reveal.</p>

<h2 id="how-to-use">How to use section navigation</h2>
<p>Section navigation can be used as a horizontal list of links. You can also set it to display vertically. Read more about <a href="#vertical-section-navigation">vertical section navigation</a>.</p>
<h3 id="horizontal-section-navigation">Horizontal section navigation</h3>
<p>Use it in a full-width column.</p>
<p>On small screens, it displays vertically if there's not enough space for all the links to display horizontally. (It uses JavaScript to do this.)</p>
<p>Put the component near the top of the page. Users may not see it if it is further down. You can put it before or after the main heading (<code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>).</p>
<p>If you put the component before your <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>, put it before the <code>&lt;main&gt;</code> element of the page. This means it is skipped when the skip link is used.</p>
<p>Unlike the navigation in the header, one of the items in section navigation should always be highlighted as the current page. This item remains a link, but uses black text.</p>
<p>Each item in the navigation is a link to a separate full page with a different URL. If you use the component for filtering a list or table, update the page's URL with a query string instead.</p>


<h4>Making page titles and headings unique</h4>
<p>Make sure each page linked from the section navigation has a unique <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> and a unique browser page title (<code>&lt;title&gt;</code>). This helps screen reader users who navigate by headings know when a page has changed. It also helps users who bookmark a page.</p>
<p>There are different ways to do this, depending on where you put the section navigation. For example, if the section navigation is near to the <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>, you can keep the visual heading as-is and add a hidden span after it that names the current page. Screen readers will announce both parts, while sighted users only see the main heading.</p>
  
{{ designExample({
  group: "components",
  item: "section-navigation",
  type: "heading-with-hidden-text"
}) }}

<p>The page <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> should also include the page name, for example: Cases – Today – Service name – NHS.</p>
<p>Other ways to make headings unique include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>using a <a href="/design-system/styles/typography#headings-with-captions">heading with a caption</a>, for example you could have a caption "Today" appear above the heading text "Cases"</li>
  <li>writing a different heading for each page, such as "Today's cases"</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="vertical-section-navigation">Vertical section navigation</h3>
<p>If your labels are long or there's not enough horizontal space, use the <code>vertical</code> option to keep section navigation stacked at all screen sizes. You can combine this with columns to provide a side navigation.</p>

{{ designExample({
  group: "components",
  item: "section-navigation",
  type: "vertical"
}) }}

<h3 id="labelling-and-ordering-links">Labelling and ordering links</h3>
<p>Consider how many links to include in the navigation. Take into account link text length and how the navigation displays responsively. Keep link text as short as possible.</p>
<p>Make sure that the link text reflects the heading of the page it links to.</p> 
<p>Decide on the default page to load. Generally it's best to order links from most to least used, with the most-used link being the first in the list and the page that's open by default. However, you can choose a different order. For example, if there is a chronological or workflow order, the first in the list may not be the most useful one to display by default.</p>

<h3 id="badges">Badges</h3>
<p>You can add a badge to a section navigation link to show a count or status label. Keep the visible label short. You can add visually hidden text to give additional context for screen reader users.</p>
  
{{ designExample({
  group: "components",
  item: "section-navigation",
  type: "badges"
}) }}

<h3 id="dark-backgrounds">Section navigation on dark backgrounds</h3>
<p>Use the <code>nhsuk-section-navigation--reverse</code> modifier class to show white links on a dark background.</p>
<p>Make sure all users can see the section navigation. The background colour must have a contrast ratio of at least 4.5:1 with white to meet <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/Understanding/contrast-minimum.html">WCAG 2.2 success criterion 1.4.3 Contrast (minimum), level AA (W3C)</a>.</p>

{{ designExample({
  group: "components",
  item: "section-navigation",
  type: "reverse"
}) }}

